<section id="features" class="section">
  <h2>Why siptty</h2>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Full desk-phone parity</h3>
      <p>Register, call, hold, transfer, conference, BLF, and presence — from the terminal.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Hackable SIP stack</h3>
      <p>Override any header, spoof devices, and craft requests for testing and debugging.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Live SIP trace</h3>
      <p>Integrated trace and dialog view for real-time inspection without leaving the UI.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Ships as one binary</h3>
      <p>PyInstaller packaging delivers a single download-and-run tool.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="architecture" class="section section--accent">
  <h2>Architecture</h2>
  <div class="columns">
    <div>
      <p>
        Textual drives the async UI while PJSIP runs on worker threads.
        siptty bridges these with a dedicated engine layer that normalizes events and commands.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Async Textual TUI + keyboard-first workflows</li>
        <li>SIP engine layer wraps pjsua2 and emits typed events</li>
        <li>Thread-safe handoff via call_from_thread()</li>
        <li>BLF + presence subscriptions managed centrally</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="terminal terminal--compact">
      <pre>
Textual UI
    │
    │ call_from_thread()
    ▼
SIP Engine (Python)
    │
    ▼
pjsua2 / PJSIP
    │
    ▼
UDP/TCP/TLS + RTP
      </pre>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

